,{"name":"Kerfoot","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Cheshire):","habitational name, probably from Carefoot, near Myerscough (Lancashire).","possibly a variant of   Griffith  ."]},{"name":"Griffes","meanings":["Welsh: altered form of   Griffith  ."]},{"name":"Griffeth","meanings":["Altered form of   Griffith  ."]},{"name":"Griffiths","meanings":["Welsh (Glamorgan and western England): Anglicized form of the patronymic <i>(ap) Gruffudd</i>, from Old Welsh <i>Grippiud</i> (see   Griffith  )."]},{"name":"Griffth","meanings":["Variant of   Griffith  ."]},{"name":"Griffitt","meanings":["Altered form of   Griffith  ."]}]},{"name":"Vychan","type":"LAST","meanings":["Welsh: A Welsh name of great antiquity, from vyckan, little, small; i.e. small in stature. Compare the surname Bychan and the Armoric Le Bihan."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Lady","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>lavedi</i>, <i>levedi</i>, <i>ladi</i> ‘lady, female head of a household, woman, wife’ (Old English <i>hlǣfdige</i>). As a man's name it may have been used in mockery, or be short for occupational names such as <b>Ladyman</b>.","Polish: variant of   Lada  .","Hungarian (<b>Ládi</b>): habitational name for someone from Lád in Borsod County or Lad in Somogy County."],"variants":[{"name":"Lada","meanings":["‘Morning dew’; also ‘generosity’."]}]},{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Maud Griffith Vychan x was born about 1378, in Caernarfonshire, Wales. She had at least 1 son with Lord Griffith Vychan of Llai."},"et":{"about 1378–":"umbes 1378–Surnud","1374–Male":"1374–Surnud","1400–1461":"1400–1461","1378–Female":"1378–Surnud","1400":"1400","1378":"1378","about 1378":"umbes 1378","1374":"1374","1461":"1461","Caernarfonshire, Wales":"Caernarfonshire, Wales"},"fi":{"about 1378–":"noin 1378–Kuollut","1374–Male":"1374–Kuollut","1400–1461":"1400–1461","1378–Female":"1378–Kuollut","1400":"1400","1378":"1378","about 1378":"noin 1378","1374":"1374","1461":"1461","Caernarfonshire, Wales":"Caernarfonshire, Wales"},"fr":{"about 1378–":"environ 1378–Décédée","1374–Male":"1374–Décédé","1400–1461":"1400–1461","1378–Female":"1378–Décédée","1400":"1400","1378":"1378","about 1378":"environ 1378","1374":"1374","1461":"1461","Caernarfonshire, Wales":"Caernarfonshire, Galles","lifeSummary":"Lady Maud Griffith Vychan x est née environ 1378, à Caernarfonshire, Galles. Elle a eu au moins 1 fils avec Lord Griffith Vychan of Llai."},"de":{"about 1378–":"um 1378–Verstorben","1374–Male":"1374–Verstorben","1400–1461":"1400–1461","1378–Female":"1378–Verstorben","1400":"1400","1378":"1378","about 1378":"um 1378","1374":"1374","1461":"1461","Caernarfonshire, Wales":"Caernarfonshire, Wales","lifeSummary":"Lady Maud Griffith Vychan x wurde um 1378 in Caernarfonshire, Wales geboren. Sie hatte mi